ondon mayoralty race|date=7 November 2019|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" data-sort-value=\"2019-10-05\" | 30 October\u20134 November 2019\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 1,175\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''45%'''\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 23%\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 7%\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 8%\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 13%\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 4%\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 22%\n| <!-- Khan -->    style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''44%'''\n| <!-- Bailey --->  25%\n| <!-- Berry --->   \u2014\n| <!-- Benita --->  \u2014\n| <!-- Stewart ---> \u2014\n| <!-- LEAD --->    style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 19%\n|-\n| <!-- Khan --->    style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''33%'''\n| <!-- Bailey --->  \u2014\n| <!-- Berry --->   25%\n| <!-- Benita --->  \u2014 \n| <!-- Stewart ---> \u2014\n| <!-- LEAD --->    style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 8%\n|-\n| <!-- Khan --->    style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''35%'''\n| <!-- Bailey --->  \u2014\n| <!-- Berry --->   \u2014\n| <!-- Benita --->  22%\n| <!-- Stewart ---> \u2014\n| <!-- LEAD --->    style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 13%\n|-\n| <!-- Khan --->    style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''36%'''\n| <!-- Bailey --->  \u2014\n| <!-- Berry --->   \u2014\n| <!-- Benita --->  \u2014 \n| <!-- Stewart ---> 25%\n| <!-- LEAD --->    style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 11%\n|-\n|[[YouGov]]/[[Queen Mary University of London|QMUL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khans-bid-for-second-term-as-mayor-of-london-hit-by-labour-s-brexit-fallout-a4141816.html|title=Labour Brexit fallout hits Sadiq Khan's Mayor of London bid|date=14 May 2019|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=\"2019-05-10\" | 7\u201310 May 2019\n|1,015\n| style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''43%'''\n| 23%\n| 16%\n| 10%\n| \u2013\n| 8%\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 20%\n| style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''64%'''\n| 36%\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 28%\n|-\n|[[YouGov]]/[[Queen Mary University of London|QMUL]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murphy |first=Joe |title=Sadiq 'enters mayor race with commanding lead over Tory rival' |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/2020-london-mayor-election-sadiq-khan-enters-race-with-commanding-lead-over-tory-shaun-bailey-a4013911.html|work=Evening Standard|language=en|date=11 December 2018|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=\"2018-12-06\"| 3\u20136 December 2018\n|1,020\n| style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''55%'''\n| 28%\n| 7%{{Efn|The poll question included Si\u00e2n Berry as the Green Party candidate, even though she had not been selected at that time.}}\n| 4%\n| \u2013\n| 6%\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 27%\n| style=\"background:#FFE0E0\" |'''62%'''\n| 38%\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};color:#FFFFFF;\"| 24%\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{London elections}}\n{{United Kingdom local elections, 2021}}\n\n[[Category:2021 in London|Mayoral election]]\n[[Category:Mayoral elections in London|2021]]\n[[Category:2021 English local elections|London mayoral election]]\n[[Category:Elections postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|London mayoral election, 2021]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 2021 London mayoral election\n| country           = \n| type              = presidential\n| ongoing           = yes\n| previous_election = 2016 London mayoral election\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| next_election     = 2024 London mayoral election\n| next_year         = ''2024''\n| election_date     = 2021\n| turnout           = \n| title             = [[Mayor of London|Mayor]]\n\n| 1blank            = 1st&nbsp;Round&nbsp;vote\n| 2blank            = Percentage \n| 3blank            = 2nd&nbsp;Round&nbsp;vote\n| 4blank            = Percentage\n\n| image1            = [[File:Sadiq Khan 2017.jpg|150x150px]]\n| candidate1        = [[Sadiq Khan]]\n| party1            = Labour Party (UK)\n| 1data1            = \n| 2data1            = \n| 3data1            = \n| 4data1            = \n\n| image2            = [[File:Shaun Bailey.jpg|150x150px]]\n| candidate2        = [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]]\n| party2            = Conservative Party (UK)\n| 1data2            = \n| 2data2            = \n| 3data2            = \n| 4data2            = \n\n| image3            = [[File:Si\u00e2n Berry, 2018 (cropped).jpg|150x150px]]\n| candidate3        = [[Si\u00e2n Berry]]\n| party3            = Green Party of England and Wales\n| 1data3            = \n| 2data3            = \n| 3data3            = \n| 4data3            = \n\n| map_image         = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| before_election   = [[Sadiq Khan]]\n| before_party      = Labour Party (UK)\n| after_election    = \n| after_party       = \n}}\nThe '''2021 London mayoral election''' is to be held in May 2021 to elect the [[mayor of London]]. It will be held simultaneously with the [[2020 London Assembly election|elections for the London Assembly]] and [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|other local elections]]. The Mayor and Assembly elections were to be held on 7 May 2020, but on 13 March 2020 it was announced the election would be postponed until 2021 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Local elections postponed for a year over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe position of Mayor of London is currently held by [[Sadiq Khan]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], who was elected in [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]] with 44.2% of the first-round votes and 56.8% of the second-round votes.\n\n== Background ==\nThe mayor of London has a range of responsibilities covering policing, transport, housing, planning, economic development, arts, culture and the environment, controlling a budget of around \u00a317 billion per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=What the Mayor of London and the London Assembly Do|url=http://www.londonelects.org.uk/im-voter/what-mayor-london-and-london-assembly-do|website=londonelects.org.uk|publisher=London Elects|accessdate=26 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503084949/https://londonelects.org.uk/im-voter/what-mayor-london-and-london-assembly-do|archive-date=3 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Mayors are elected for a period of four years, with no limit to the number of terms served.<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A: London mayoral and London Assembly elections 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17546714|work=BBC News|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> Under the [[Greater London Authority Act 1999]], mayoral elections are held on the first Thursday in May in the fourth calendar year following the previous election, unless varied by an order of the Secretary of State. The incumbent, [[Sadiq Khan]], a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], was elected in the [[2016 London mayoral election|2016 election]], defeating the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate, [[Zac Goldsmith]].\n\nIn the [[2018 London local elections|2018 local elections across Greater London]] the Labour party increased its number of council seats to the highest level since 1978. Both the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and the [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] also gained seats across London. In the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament elections]], the Lib Dems came first in London; winning the most votes in the [[London (European Parliament constituency)|London region]] with 27% and gaining three MEPs, their best result in the party's history. The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] came second, with 24% of the vote, losing two seats and ending up with two MEPs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-48417664|title=Lib Dems top London European vote|date=27 May 2019|access-date=30 May 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[The Brexit Party]] gained two MEPs and Greens won 12.5% of the vote, holding their one seat. The Conservative Party failed to get a single MEP elected in London for the first time in the history of the party. In the [[2019 United Kingdom general election in England#London|2019 general election]], there was no net change in the number of seats for each party, although several seats changed hand. The biggest changes in vote share were for Labour, who saw a fall of 6.5%, and the Liberal Democrats, who were up 6.1%.\n\n==Electoral system==\nThe election will use a [[The Supplementary Vote|supplementary vote]] system, in which voters express a first and a second preference for candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonelects.org.uk/im-voter/how-vote|title=How to Vote|work=London Elects|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> \n* If a candidate receives more than 50% of the first preference vote, that candidate wins.\n* If no candidate receives more than 50% of first preference votes, the top two candidates proceed to a second round and all other candidates are eliminated.\n* The first preference votes for the remaining two candidates stand in the final count. \n* Voters' ballots whose first and second preference candidates are eliminated are discarded.\n* Voters whose first preference candidates have been eliminated and whose second preference candidate is one of the top two have their second preference votes added to that candidate's count.\nThis means that the winning candidate has the support of a majority of voters who expressed a preference among the top two.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Elledge|first1=Jonnk|url=https://londonist.com/2012/05/london-elections-how-the-voting-system-works |title=London Elections: How The Voting System Works |publisher=The Londonist |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=21 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAll [[Elections in the United Kingdom#Registration procedure|registered electors]] ([[British citizen|British]], [[Irish citizen|Irish]], [[Commonwealth citizen|Commonwealth]] and [[European Union]] citizens) living in London aged 18 or over will be entitled to vote in the mayoral election. Those who are temporarily away from London (for example, away working, on holiday, in student accommodation or in hospital) will also be entitled to vote in the mayoral election. The deadline to [[Elections in the United Kingdom#Registration procedure|register to vote]] in the election will be announced nearer the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonelects.org.uk/im-voter/how-register-vote|title=How to Register to Vote|work=London Elects|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nNominations for candidates was scheduled to open on 23 March 2020, and the list of mayoral candidates was going to be released on 1 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite website|url=https://www.londonelects.org.uk/im-candidate/nominations|title=Nominations|date=1 January 2020|work=Greater London Returning Officer|access-date=1 January 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Campaign ==\nThe incumbent mayor [[Sadiq Khan]] announced in June 2018 that he intended to stand for re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-20/sadiq-khan-will-run-for-london-mayor-again-in-2020/|title=Sadiq Khan Vote Ken for mayor\n|work=ITV News|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en}}</ref> Later that year, he was automatically re-selected to be [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] candidate after receiving sufficient nominations from local party groups and affiliated trade unions to avoid an open selection.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Wearmouth |first=Rachel |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/london-mayor-sadiq-khan-sees-off-threat-to-his-bid-for-re-election_uk_5b9b7ab2e4b04d32ebf73b9e|title=Sadiq Khan sees off threat to his bid for re-election as London Mayor|date=14 September 2018|work=HuffPost UK|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last= Dallison |first= Paul |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/sadiq-khan-will-be-labour-candidate-in-next-london-mayoral-race/|title=Sadiq Khan will be Labour candidate in next London mayoral race|date=14 September 2018|work=POLITICO|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> His re-selection followed speculation that a figure from the left of his party could challenge him for the candidacy given Khan's disagreements with national party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Khan announced in the new year part of his election platform will be to deliver a \"green new deal for the city\", by making London [[carbon neutral]] by 2030 and [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport|opposing the third runway]] at [[Heathrow Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chappell |first1=Elliot |title=Sadiq Khan announces green new deal for London - LabourList |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/sadiq-khan-announces-green-new-deal-for-london/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=[[LabourList]] |date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Conservative Party selected [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]] as its candidate in September 2018. In his selection, he emphasised fighting crime, and proposed \"maximising\" CCTV coverage of London as an alternative to increasing the number of police officers, as well as automatic jail terms for those who commit [[Acid throwing|acid attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Proctor |first=Kate|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/sadiq-khan-is-fuelling-our-feeling-of-being-unsafe-says-favourite-for-tory-mayor-ticket-a3880276.html|title=Favourite for Tory mayor ticket: Sadiq fuels feeling of being unsafe|work=Evening Standard|date=5 July 2018|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Staff writer |first=|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/tory-mayor-hopeful-shaun-bailey-send-thugs-carrying-acid-straight-to-jail-a3938626.html|title=Tory Mayor hopeful Shaun Bailey: send thugs carrying acid straight to jail|work=Evening Standard|date=18 September 2018|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> In the weeks after his selection, Bailey was criticised for sharing an Islamophobic tweet attacking Sadiq Khan,<ref>{{Cite news|last= Watts |first=Joe |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/shaun-bailey-islamophobia-sadiq-khan-london-mayor-tory-party-conservatives-a8558521.html|title=Conservative candidate for London Mayor embroiled in new Sadiq Khan Islamophobia row|work=The Independent|date=27 September 2018|access-date=11 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> as well as controversial views he had previously published on multiculturalism, Islam and Hinduism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/oct/03/tories-london-mayor-pick-shaun-bailey-multiculturalism-robs-britain-of-its-community|title=Tory London mayoral pick under fire for remarks about Muslims and Hindus|last=Sabbagh|first=Dan|work=The Guardian|language=en|date=3 October 2018|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> He will be the first Conservative mayoral candidate to simultaneously stand in the [[2020 London Assembly election|concurrent London Assembly election]], which led some to question how confident he was in his own chances of winning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/269721/shaun-bailey-stand-2020-london-assembly-elections-despite|title=Shaun Bailey to stand in London Assembly elections despite mayoral bid|last=Rogers|first=Alexandra|date=26 November 2018|work=City AM|language=en|access-date=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Green Party chose [[Si\u00e2n Berry]], who had previously been their mayoral candidate in the [[2008 London mayoral election|2008]] and [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]] elections, to represent them in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/14/green-party-sian-berry-stand-london-mayoral-election-2020|title=Green party's Si\u00e2n Berry to run for London mayor again in 2020|last=Walker|first=Peter |date=14 February 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 February 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> She launched her campaign with a focus on housing, calling for a \"people's land bank\" to give communities more control over unused land and buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-47237025|title=Green Party chooses mayoral candidate|work=BBC News|date=14 February 2019|access-date=14 February 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n[[Siobhan Benita]] was selected to be the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate on 21 November 2018.<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\">{{cite news|last= Murphy|first=Joe |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/mayor/siobhan-benita-second-mayor-bid-will-address-unfinished-business-a3937771.html|title=Siobhan Benita: Second Mayor bid will address 'unfinished business'|work=Evening Standard|date=17 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Lib Dem Press Office on Twitter\">{{cite tweet |author=Lib Dem Press Office |user=LibDemPress |number=1065285835329888258 |date=21 November 2018 |title= We are delighted to announce that @SiobhanBenita will be the @LibDems candidate for the London Mayoral elections in May 2020, and will lead the campaign for the London Assembly elections.}}</ref> Benita ran as an independent candidate in the [[2012 London mayoral election]], coming fifth with 3.8% of the first preference votes, behind fourth-placed Liberal Democrat candidate [[Brian Paddick]], who received 4.2%. Benita criticised Khan's response to knife crime in London.<ref>{{cite news|last=Osley |first=Richard|url=http://camdennewjournal.com/article/mayor-too-weak-on-knife-crime-warns-lib-dem-challenger-siobhan-benita|title=Mayor too weak on knife crime, warns Lib Dem challenger Siobhan Benita|work=Camden New Journal|date=29 November 2018}}</ref> In August 2019, she supported calls for the [[Cannabis in the United Kingdom#Advocacy for law reform|decriminalisation of cannabis]]. She also said that her campaign priorities are around knife crime and serious violence, air quality and the environment, more affordable housing, and opposing Brexit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/the-cannabis-debate-make-drug-legal-says-lib-dem-mayoral-hopeful-siobhan-benita-a4209711.html|title=Make cannabis legal, says Lib Dem mayoral hopeful Siobhan Benita|date=9 August 2019|website=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[UK Independence Party]] leader [[Nigel Farage]] announced in August 2018 that he was considering running as the UKIP candidate, claiming that he would be more successful than the Conservatives.<ref name=\"Farage_FT\">{{Cite news|last=Pickard |first=Jim |url=https://www.ft.com/content/24fe9bd6-aba7-11e8-89a1-e5de165fa619|title=Nigel Farage considers running for London mayor|work=Financial Times|language=en-GB|date=30 August 2018|access-date=11 October 2018}}</ref> However, he subsequently left UKIP.\n\nOn 4 October 2019, [[Rory Stewart]], who had been a Conservative MP and came fifth in the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election]], but was then expelled from their Parliamentary group for his opposition to a no deal [[Brexit]] and was sitting as an independent MP, announced he was standing as an independent candidate for the London mayoralty.<ref name=ES191004>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rory-stewart-to-stand-for-london-mayor-after-quitting-conservative-party-and-stepping-down-as-mp-a4254056.html|title=Rory Stewart: I'll stand for London Mayor as an independent candidate|date=4 October 2019|website=Evening Standard|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-tories-brexit-article-50-boris-johnson-live-news|title=Brexit: Johnson 'will seek extension if no withdrawal deal agreed in time' \u2013 as it happened|first1=Mattha|last1=Busby|first2=Lisa|last2=O'Carroll|date=4 October 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> He left the House of Commons when he did not contest a seat in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|December 2019 general election]].<ref name=ES191004/>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, it was announced the election would be postponed until 2021 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Local elections postponed for a year over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\n===Labour Party===\nThe incumbent mayor [[Sadiq Khan]] became Labour's candidate after more than half of local parties and party affiliates in [[London]] voted to automatically reselect him.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eaton |first=George|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2018/09/sadiq-khan-reselected-labour-s-london-mayoral-candidate-after-winning-party|title=Sadiq Khan reselected as Labour's London mayoral candidate after winning party ballot|work=New Statesman|language=en|date=14 September 2018|access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> Comedian [[Eddie Izzard]] and Tottenham MP [[David Lammy]] had previously been suggested as potential candidates.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/09/22/top-7-favourites-to-win-the-2020-london-mayoral-contest-can-khan/|title=Top 7 favourites to win the 2020 London Mayoral contest: can Khan win?|last1=Wood|first1=Richard|website=hitc.com|publisher=Here Is The City|language=en|date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party===\n[[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]] was selected as the candidate of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in September 2018. Bailey has been a member of the [[London Assembly]] since 2016, having previously worked as a youth worker and as a special adviser to [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-choose-ex-youth-worker-shaun-bailey-to-take-on-london-mayor-sadiq-khan-gqmh8z3xn|title=Tories choose ex-youth worker Shaun Bailey to take on London mayor Sadiq Khan|last=Zeffman|first=Henry |date=29 September 2018|work=The Times|access-date=24 January 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"torieschoose\">{{Cite news|last=Proctor|first=Kate|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tories-choose-shaun-bailey-for-mayoral-candidate-to-take-on-sadiq-khan-a3948091.html|title=Tories choose Shaun Bailey for mayoral candidate to take on Sadiq|work=Evening Standard|date=28 September 2018|access-date=28 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe party had started the process for selecting their candidate in June 2018.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jun/01/justine-greening-tipped-as-tory-candidate-for-london-mayor|title=Justine Greening tipped as Tory candidate for London mayor|first=Jessica|last=Elgot|date=1 June 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/287760/conservative-mayoral-candidate-open-all-except-die-hard|title=Tories open London mayoral candidacy to all - except die-hard Remainers|work=City AM|last=Neilan|first=Catherine|date=18 June 2018|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625161306/http://www.cityam.com/287760/conservative-mayoral-candidate-open-all-except-die-hard|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' reported that more than twenty prospective candidates applied, mostly from local government. A longlist of ten was published in July 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /> Following interviews, the party produced a shortlist of three for London members of the Conservative Party to vote on<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/03/top-tories-shy-away-from-2020-london-mayoral-race|title=Top Tories shy away from 2020 London mayoral race|first=Pippa|last=Crerar|date=3 July 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> using a [[Ranked voting methods|preferential voting]] system.<ref name=torieschoose /> To vote, members had to reside in London and have been members on 26 June 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"chome2018-07-23\">{{cite web | url = https://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2018/07/the-conservatives-have-a-strong-final-shortlist-for-london-mayoral-candidate-now-the-members-decide.html | title = What the London Mayoral selection short-list tells us. And what the successful candidate should do | last = Phibbs | first = Harry | date = 23 July 2018 | publisher = [[ConservativeHome]] | access-date = 24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nBailey had been endorsed in the party's selection process by the [[London Evening Standard|''Evening Standard'']], as well as Conservative Police and Crime Commissioners [[Anthony Stansfeld]], [[David Lloyd (police commissioner)|David Lloyd]], [[Matthew Scott (police commissioner)|Matthew Scott]] and [[Roger Hirst]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=ES Comment|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/comment/comment/evening-standard-comment-we-back-shaun-bailey-as-the-tory-mayoral-candidate-snapping-the-sevenups-a3938726.html|title=Evening Standard comment: We back Shaun Bailey as the Tory mayoral candidate; Snapping the seven-ups|work=Evening Standard|date=18 September 2018|access-date=22 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Murphy|first=Joe|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/police-chiefs-back-tory-mayoral-hopeful-shaun-bailey-to-deal-with-london-crime-and-round-on-clueless-a3930046.html|title=Police chiefs back Tory mayoral hopeful Shaun Bailey to solve crime|work=Evening Standard|date=7 September 2018|access-date=22 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote begin\n| title = Conservative London mayoral candidate selection| source=<ref name=torieschoose />\n}}\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| candidate = [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]]\n| fullwidthvotes=3904 | r1votes=3164 | r1votespercent=43.2 | r2votes=740 | totalpercent=55.1%\n}}\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| candidate = [[Andrew Boff]]\n| fullwidthvotes=3904 | r1votes=2591 | r1votespercent=35.4 | r2votes=595 | totalpercent=44.9%\n}}\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| candidate = [[Joy Morrissey]] \n| fullwidthvotes=3904 | r1votes=1566 | r1votespercent=21.4 |\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{|  class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n| '''Selection process'''\n|-\n|\n'''Shortlisted'''\n* [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]], Member of the [[London Assembly]] since 2016<ref name=\"BBC2018-07-23\">{{cite news | title = London mayoral race: Tories shortlist three candidates  | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 23 July 2018 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-44923525 | access-date = 24 July 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Boff]], Member of the [[London Assembly]] since 2008<ref name=BBC2018-07-23 />\n* [[Joy Morrissey]], councillor in Ealing since 2014<ref name=BBC2018-07-23 />\n\n'''Longlisted but not shortlisted'''\n* [[Duwayne Brooks]], former Liberal Democrat Lewisham councillor and friend of [[Stephen Lawrence]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Murphy|first=Joe|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/stephen-lawrences-friend-duwayne-brooks-calls-on-sadiq-khan-to-quit-its-time-the-mayor-took-a3858441.html|title=Stephen Lawrence's friend Duwayne Brooks calls for Sadiq Khan to quit over violence surge|work=Evening Standard|date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Alison Cork]], interiors expert and entrepreneur<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Kevin Davis, former leader of [[Kingston upon Thames London Borough Council|Kingston upon Thames council]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murphy|first=Joe|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/exwest-end-actor-declares-dream-to-be-mayor-as-first-official-tory-candidate-a3875176.html|title=Ex-West End actor declares dream to be Mayor as first official Tory candidate|work=Evening Standard|date=29 June 2018|access-date=3 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Simone Finn, Baroness Finn|Simone Finn]], member of the House of Lords<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Ruby McGregor-Smith]], member of the House of Lords<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Kulveer Ranger]], former Director of Environment, Digital London and Environment for former mayor Boris Johnson<ref name=\"auto4\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Shipman|first=Tim|title=London mayoral election: Male, pale and stale candidates off the list|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/london-mayoral-election-male-pale-and-stale-candidates-off-the-list-h20s8fv0h|date=3 June 2018|work=The Times}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[Andrew Rosindell]], MP for [[Romford (UK Parliament constituency)|Romford]] since 2001<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennett|first=Owen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/andrew-rosindell-london-mayor_uk_5b3cf9bce4b07b827cbcf939|title=Tory MP who thinks EU passports are a national humiliation wants to be London Mayor|date=4 July 2018|work=HuffPost}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Applied but not longlisted'''\n*[[Nimco Ali]], director of [[Daughters of Eve]], [[Women's Equality Party]] candidate for [[Hornsey and Wood Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Hornsey and Wood Green]] in 2017<ref>{{cite news|last= Diary|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/the-londoner-mercer-takes-aim-at-private-pike-a3880061.html|title=The Londoner: Mercer takes aim at 'Private Pike'|work=Evening Standard|date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Richard Tice]], businessman and campaigner (joined the [[Brexit Party]] in 2019)<ref name=\"auto7\">{{Cite news|last=Bennett|first=Owen |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/richard-tice-london-mayor-conservative_uk_5b361afae4b0f3c2219ffb32 |title=Brexit 'Bad Boy' Richard Tice puts himself forward to be Tory candidate for London Mayor|date=29 June 2018|work=HuffPost|access-date=3 July 2018 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n'''Previously discussed as potential candidates'''\n*[[Nick de Bois]], MP for [[Enfield North (UK Parliament constituency)|Enfield North]] from 2010 to 2015<ref name=\"Wearmouth_HP\">{{cite news|last=Wearmouth|first=Rachel|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/justine-greening-rules-herself-out-of-london-mayoral-contest_uk_5b32a6a5e4b0b745f17890ec|title=Justine Greening rules herself out of race to be next London Mayor|date=26 June 2018|work=HuffPost}}</ref>\n*[[Karren Brady]], life peer since 2014<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Laura|url=https://www.ft.com/content/73e48902-4f97-11e8-9471-a083af05aea7|title=London election results allow Tories to dream of being mayor|work=Financial Times|date=5 May 2018|url-access=subscription |access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/devolution/2018/07/everyone-wins-james-cleverly-mayoral-bid-including-sadiq-khan|title=Everyone wins from a James Cleverly mayoral bid \u2013 including Sadiq Khan|work=New Statesman|date=2 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Sol Campbell]], former footballer<ref>{{cite news|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|title=Sol Campbell sets sights on 2020 London mayoral election|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/social-affairs/politics/news/68127/sol-campbell-sets-sights-2020-london-mayoral-election|work=Politics Home|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n*[[James Cleverly]], MP for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]] since 2015<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref name=\"auto2\" /><ref name=\"auto7\" />\n*[[Sajid Javid]], then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], MP for [[Bromsgrove (UK Parliament constituency)|Bromsgrove]] since 2010<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n*[[Jo Johnson]], MP for [[Orpington (UK Parliament constituency)|Orpington]] from 2010 to 2019; brother of former mayor Boris Johnson<ref name=\"PoliticoEU\">{{cite news|last=Le Conte|first=Marie |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/tories-eye-the-race-to-take-on-london-mayor-sadiq-khan/ |title=Tories eye race to take on Sadiq Khan|work=[[Politico Europe]]|date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Justine Greening]], MP for [[Putney (UK Parliament constituency)|Putney]] from 2005 to 2019, former [[Secretary of State for Education]] (2016\u20132018)<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|last=Crerrar|first=Pippa|title=London Tories 'eyeball' PM as they plan unit to take on Labour|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/london-tories-eyeball-theresa-may-as-they-plan-unit-to-take-on-labour-a3650316.html|work=Evening Standard|date=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\" />\n*[[Syed Kamall]], former [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[London (European Parliament constituency)|London]] (2005 to 2019) <ref>{{cite news|last=Murphy|first=Joe|title='Tories must modernise or we'll lose every safe seat in London'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/tories-must-modernise-or-we-ll-lose-every-safe-seat-in-london-a3648256.html|work=Evening Standard|date=2 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jun/26/tory-justine-greening-rules-herself-out-of-london-mayoral-race|title=Tory Justine Greening rules herself out of London mayoral race|first=Pippa|last=Crerar|date=26 June 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\" />\n*[[Munira Mirza]], former deputy mayor for education and culture of London<ref name=\"PoliticoEU\" /><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/285462/elections-over-tories-must-find-their-next-london-mayor|title=Elections over, the Tories must find their next London mayor|last=Elliott|first=Matthew|date=9 May 2018|access-date=25 June 2018|work=City AM|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625143235/http://www.cityam.com/285462/elections-over-tories-must-find-their-next-london-mayor|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[George Osborne]], editor of the [[London Evening Standard]], former [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] (2010\u20132016) and MP for [[Tatton (UK Parliament constituency)|Tatton]] (2001\u20132017)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hope|first1=Christopher|title=George Osborne refuses to rule out a return to public life as an MP or London Mayor|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/07/george-osborne-refuses-rule-return-public-life-mp-london-mayor/|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=7 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wearmouth_HP\" />\n*[[Ed Vaizey]], MP for [[Wantage (UK Parliament constituency)|Wantage]] since 2005, former [[Minister of State for Digital and Culture|Minister of State for Culture, Communications and Creative Industries]] (2010\u20132016)<ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Iain|author-link=Iain Dale|title=Tory MP does not rule out standing against Sadiq Khan over Uber ruling|url=http://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/iain-dale/tory-mp-not-rule-out-standing-sadiq-khan-uber/|work=LBC|date=22 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Liberal Democrats===\n[[Siobhan Benita]], a former senior civil servant and 2012 independent candidate for London mayor, was selected to be the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate on 21 November 2018.<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\" /> The other shortlisted candidates were anti-Brexit campaigner and former and 2020 London Assembly candidate Rob Blackie, [[Ebookers]] founder [[Dinesh Dhamija]], and former parliamentary candidate, consultant and 2020 London Assembly candidate Lucy Salek.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pack |first=Mark|url=https://www.markpack.org.uk/156414/lib-dem-london-shortlist/|title=Lib Dem shortlist for London Mayor and GLA list published |website= markpack.org.uk |publisher= Mark Pack|date=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"standard.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"blackietweet\">{{cite tweet|number=1049324940963577856|user=robblackie|title=I'm delighted to have made the shortlist for Lib Dem Mayor of London candidate, as well as the GLA shortlist. I believe London should be a city of opportunity for everyone, and that the most important job the mayor should be doing right now is fighting Brexit.|date=8 October 2018|access-date=9 October 2018|last=Blackie|first=Rob}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bush |first=Stephen|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/elections/2018/06/why-are-liberal-democrats-celebrating-defeat-lewisham-east|title=Why are the Liberal Democrats celebrating defeat in Lewisham East?|work=New Statesman|date=15 June 2018}}</ref> Benita came first among first preferences, but with less than half the votes. After last-placed Lucy Salek was eliminated and second preferences among her voters tallied, Benita had a majority of the votes cast and was chosen as the party's candidate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pack |first=Mark|url=https://www.markpack.org.uk/156678/siobhan-benita-london-mayor-candidate/|title=Lib Dems announce Siobhan Benita as London Mayoral candidate |website= markpack.org.uk |publisher= Mark Pack|date=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nSiobhan Benita launched her mayoral campaign on 13 February 2020. She said she wants to [[Drug liberalization#Drug legalization|legalise]] [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] in London in a bid to tackle rising levels of knife crime. She stated she would like to see [[Pilot experiment|pilots]] for legal regulated cannabis across London in order to remove power and money from gangs, free up police time to tackle serious crimes, and raise millions of pounds in tax, which could be invested in youth services and support those addicted to harder drugs. She has also pledged to cut violent crime, cut air pollution, declared an aim to reach zero-carbon by 2030 and reopen closed police stations.<ref>{{cite news |date= 13 February 2020 |title= London mayoral race: Legalise cannabis, says Lib Dem candidate |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51487482 |work= BBC News |access-date= 20 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Benita |first= Siobhan |date= 14 February 2020 |title= London has a knife crime crisis \u2013 as mayor, here's how I'd fix it |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/london-knife-crime-sadiq-khan-gangs-cannabis-a9333841.html |work= The Independent |access-date= 20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote begin\n| title = Liberal Democrat London mayoral candidate selection| source=<ref name=torieschoose />\n}}\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| candidate = [[Siobhan Benita]]\n| fullwidthvotes=1771 | r1votes=1548 | r1votespercent=46.2 | r2votes=223 | totalpercent=54.2%\n}}\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| candidate = Rob Blackie\n| fullwidthvotes=1771 | r1votes=614 | r1votespercent=18.3 | r2votes=169 | totalpercent=24.0%\n}}\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| candidate = [[Dinesh Dhamija]]\n| fullwidthvotes=1771 | r1votes=614 | r1votespercent=18.3 | r2votes=98 | totalpercent=21.8%\n}}\n\n{{Election box supplementary vote candidate with party link\n| party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| candidate = Lucy Salek\n| fullwidthvotes=1771 | r1votes=576 | r1votespercent=17.2 |\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n|'''Previously discussed as potential candidates'''\n|-\n|\n*Azi Ahmed, author, entrepreneur and Conservative candidate for [[Rochdale]] at the 2015 general election<ref name=\"libdemswooing\">{{cite news|last1=Cecil |first1=Nicholas|last2=Murphy |first2=Joe | title=Lib Dems wooing EU voters in 21 languages for town hall elections|work=Evening Standard|date=9 March 2018|page=2}}</ref>\n*Kishan Devani, former Deputy Chairman of the London Conservative Party and Conservative candidate for [[Leicester East]] at the 2015 general election<ref name=\"libdemswooing\" />\n*[[Rachel Johnson]], editor, journalist, television presenter and author; sister of former mayor [[Boris Johnson]] (joined [[Change UK]] in 2019)<ref>{{cite news|last=Revesz |first=Rachael|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rachel-johnson-liberal-democrats-mayor-2020-boris-johnson-brexit-a7710601.html|title=Boris Johnson's sister Rachel could run to be London mayor - for the Lib Dems|date=30 April 2017|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Green Party===\n[[Si\u00e2n Berry]], who has been co-leader of the Green Party since 2018 and a Member of the London Assembly since 2016, was announced as the party's mayoral candidate on 14 February 2019. She had previously been the party's candidate for mayor of London in [[2008 London mayoral election|2008]] when she came fourth with 3.2% of the first preference vote; in [[2016 London mayoral election|2016]], she came third with 5.8% of the first preference vote. Nominations had opened in November 2018 and closed in January 2019, with four candidates duly nominated.<ref>{{cite tweet |author=London Green Party |user=LonGreenParty |number=1067917125032075265 |date=28 November 2018 |title= Today we opened nominations to be our Green Party candidates for the Mayor and Assembly in 2020. We aim to run our strongest campaign ever to make London an equitable and sustainable city for all. Please consider standing for mayor or for the Assembly list.}}</ref><ref name=\"Green Party website shortlist\">{{cite web|url=https://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/2019/01/14/green-party-reveals-full-list-of-runners-for-london-mayoral-and-assembly-spots/|title=Green Party reveals full list of runners for London Mayoral and Assembly spots|website=greenparty.org.uk|publisher=The Green Party|date=14 January 2019|access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref> The other nominated candidates were former deputy leader and candidate for the UK Parliament, London Assembly and European Parliament [[Shahrar Ali]], actor and Cities of London and Westminster Dec 2019 candidate Zack Polanski, as well as former senior civil servant, general election candidate and London Assembly candidate Peter Underwood.<ref name=\"Green Party website shortlist\" /><ref>''Other citations:''\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/author/zack-polanski/|title=Profile: Zack Polanski|work=The Stage}}\n* {{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113182333/https://wcl.greenparty.org.uk/local-elections.html|archive-date=13 January 2019|url=https://wcl.greenparty.org.uk/local-elections.html|title=Local elections May, 2018 |website=wcl.greenparty.org.uk|publisher=West Central London Green Party}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://bright-green.org/2019/01/06/new-year-new-structures-and-new-policies-green-news-round-up-week-1/|title=New year, new structures and new policies - Green news round up week 1|date=6 January 2019|website=Bright Green|language=en-GB|access-date=12 January 2019}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://insidecroydon.com/2019/01/16/underwood-named-on-greens-shortlist-for-london-mayor/|title=Underwood named on Greens shortlist for London Mayor|first=|last=|date=16 January 2019|publisher=Inside Croydon via WordPress}}</ref>\n\n===Other candidates===\nThe following have announced their intentions to stand:\n\n* [[Count Binface]], [[Political satire|satirical candidate]] created by comedian Jon Harvey, as an independent.<ref>{{cite web |title=Count Binface to run for London Mayor |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/news/5677/count_binface_for_london_mayor/ |website=[[British Comedy Guide]] |date=27 February 2020 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n* Drillminister, London-based rapper, campaigning on reducing homelessness, improving transport, increasing mental health support, diversifying the [[Metropolitan Police Service]] and rehabilitation to curb crime and improving air quality in the capital as an independent candidate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/drillminister-mayor-of-london_uk_5e2f0a32c5b6d6767fd96c83|title=Drillminister To Run For Mayor of London, Saying Politicians Don't Represent Real Voters|first=Nadine|last=White|date=28 January 2019|via=www.huffingtonpost.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Drillminister: Why I'm running for London Mayor |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-london-51314458/drillminister-why-i-m-running-for-london-mayor |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n* [[David Kurten]], former [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] member of the [[London Assembly]] (currently sitting for the [[Brexit Alliance]]), campaigning on a [[Social_conservatism|social conservative]] platform as an independent candidate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/18191327.david-kurten-announces-run-mayor-london/|title=David Kurten announces run for Mayor of London|first=Jessie|last=Mathewson|date=28 January 2019|via=www.guardian-series.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Winston McKenzie]], activist and perennial candidate, for Unity in Action<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-51628623|title=The candidates standing to be London's mayor|date=26 February 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=27 February 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Mullins]], founder of [[Pimlico Plumbers]], as an independent<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/01/16/pimlico-plumbers-charlie-mullins-run-london-mayor-common-sense/|title=Pimlico Plumbers' Charlie Mullins to run for London Mayor on 'common sense' ticket|first=Alan|last=Tovey|date=25 June 2018|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n* Nims Obunge, pastor, as an independent<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Rosalind Readhead, as an independent, campaigning on environmental issues<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jul/23/nissan-refuses-government-request-on-qashqai-emissions|title=Nissan refuses government request on Qashqai emissions|first=Carlton|last=Reid|date=23 July 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* [[Mandu Reid]], for the [[Women's Equality Party]] (replacing [[Sue Black (computer scientist)|Sue Black]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bcswomen.bcs.org/womens-equality-party-announces-interim-leader-and-london-mayoral-candidate/|title=Women's Equality Party announces Interim Leader and London Mayoral Candidate|date=10 March 2019|website=BCSWomen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/16/womens-equality-party-candidate-pulls-out-of-london-mayoral-race|title=Women's Equality party candidate pulls out of London mayoral race|first=Kate|last=Proctor|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2020|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Rory Stewart]], former Conservative MP and [[Secretary of State for International Development]], as an independent candidate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-conservative-party|title=Rory Stewart leaves Tory party to run for London mayor|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=4 October 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n== Opinion polls ==\nThe polls below were taken when the election was expected in May 2020.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;line-height:14px\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\"| Pollster/client(s)\n! rowspan=\"3\"| Date(s)<br />conducted\n! rowspan=\"3\"| Sample size\n! colspan=\"7\" | First preference\n! colspan=\"7\" | Final round\n|-\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| [[Sadiq Khan|Khan]]\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Bailey]]\n! style=\"width:5