nyer Beach<br> [[Carita Beach]]\n|-\n|[[Merak, Banten|Merak Toll Gate]]||98||'''M R A K'''|| [[Merak, Banten|Merak Harbor]]<br>[[Sumatra]]<br>[[Kalimantan]]\n|-\n|[[Bakauheni|Bakauheni Toll Gate]]||120||'''B H N I'''||[[Bakauheni]]<br>Port Of Bakauheni\n|-\n|[[Lampung|Lampung Toll Gate]]||140||'''L M P G'''||[[Lampung]]<br>[[Palembang]]<br> [[Medan-Padang Toll Road]]\n|}\n===Interchange===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! KM !! Location !! Destination\n|-\n|00||[[Tomang]]||[[Jakarta Inner Ring Road]]\n|-\n|08||[[Kembangan, Jakarta|Kembangan]]||[[Jakarta Outer Ring Road]]\n|-\n|38||[[Balaraja]]||[[Serpong\u2013Balaraja Toll Road]] (planned)\n|-\n|140||[[Lampung]]||[[Medan-Padang Toll Road]]\n|}\n\n==Elevated section==\n{{main|Prof. Dr. Sedyatmo Toll Road}}\nIn order to avoid the flood of Ciujung river in the rainy season, the government elevated the road.\n\n==Housing exits==\nThis toll road, not just connecting cities, it also connects housing, here are some:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Toll Gate !! KM !! Housing !! Destination\n|-\n|Karang Tengah Barat||11||[[Green Lake City]]||Green Lake City, Cipondoh, Ciledug\n|-\n|Kunciran||15||[[Alam Sutera]]||Kunciran, [[Alam Sutera]], [[Serpong]]\n|-\n|Karawaci Barat||21||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lippo Village]]||rowspan=\"2\"|Karawaci, Binong, Legok\n|-\n|Karawaci Timur||20||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jakarta-Merak Toll Road}}\n[[Category:Toll roads in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Transport in Banten]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=February 2016}}\n{{infobox road\n| country = IDN\n| type = Toll Road\n| name = Jakarta\u2013Lampung Toll Road\n| maint = PT Jasa Marga Tbk and Marga Mandala Sakti\n| length_km = 140\n| direction_a = East\n| direction_b = West\n| terminus_a = [[Tomang]] Interchange\n| terminus_b = [[Lampung]]\n| cities = [[West Jakarta]], [[Tangerang Regency]], [[Tangerang]], [[Tigaraksa]], [[Lebak Regency]], [[Serang]], [[Cilegon]],[[Lampung]]\n| formed = 2019\n| history = \n| junction = [[Jakarta Inner Ring Road]]<br>[[Jakarta Outer Ring Road]] <br>[[Jakarta-Lampung Toll Road]] <br /> [[Serpong\u2013Balaraja Toll Road]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Jakarta\u2013Lampung Toll Road''' is a [[toll road]] connecting [[Jakarta]] and [[Lampung]]. The total length of this toll road is {{convert|140|km|mi|abbr=}}. This is main toll road for people who live in [[West Jakarta]] and [[Bandar Lampung]]. This toll road were also the part of [[Asian Highway 2]].\n\n==History==\nThe Toll Road is the second toll road in [[Indonesia]] after [[Jagorawi Toll Road]] in 1978. The toll has a length of 140&nbsp;km. The toll road is famous to its traffic on Karang Tengah Toll Gate. On 19 April 2017, due of heavy traffic, it was decided to demolish Karang Tengah Toll Gate. The first westbound exit is at [[Kebon Jeruk]]. The Jakarta-Lampung has only 7x7 wide of the road. The toll road is also access to [[Jakarta]], [[Tangerang]],  [[Balaraja]], [[Cikande,|Cikande]], [[Ciujung]], [[Serang]], [[Pandeglang Regency|Pandeglang]], [[Cilegon]], [[Merak, Banten|Merak]], Laut ([[Selat Sunda|SelatSunda]]), [[Bakauheni]], [[Lampung]]\n\n==Exits==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Toll Gate !! KM !! Abbreviation !! Destination\n|-\n|[[Tomang|Tomang Toll Gate]]||00||'''TOMANG'''||[[Jakarta Inner Ring Road]]<br>[[Semanggi, Surakarta|Semanggi]]<br>Angke<br>[[Cawang]]\n|-\n|[[Kebon Jeruk|Kebon Jeruk Toll Gate]]||03||'''KEBONJERUK'''||[[Kebon Jeruk]]<br>[[Kedoya]]\n|-\n|[[Kembangan|Meruya Toll Gate]]||06||'''MERUYA'''||Meruya<br>[[Kembangan, Jakarta|Kembangan]]<br>[[Joglo]]\n|-\n|[[Jakarta Outer Ring Road|Meruya Utara Toll Gate]]||07||'''MRYA UTARA'''||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Jakarta Outer Ring Road]]<br>[[Soekarno-Hatta International Airport]]\n|-\n|[[Kembangan|Kembangan Selatan Toll Gate]]||08||'''KBGN  SLTN'''\n|-\n|[[Cipondoh|Karang Tengah Barat Toll Gate]]||11||'''KTGH BARAT'''|| [[Karang Tengah]]<br>[[Cipondoh]]<br>[[Ciledug, Tangerang|Ciledug]]\n|-\n|[[Alam Sutera|Kunciran Toll Gate]]||15||'''KUNCIRAN'''||[[Kunciran]]<br>[[Alam Sutera]] <br>[[Serpong, Tangerang|Serpong]]\n|-\n|[[Tangerang|Tangerang Toll Gate]]||18||'''TANGERANG'''||[[Tangerang]]<br> Serpong <br> Pakulonan\n|-\n|[[Karawaci|Karawaci Toll Gate]]||21||'''KARAWACI'''||[[Karawaci, Tangerang|Karawaci]]<br>Binong<br>[[Legok]]\n|-\n|[[Curug, Tangerang|Bitung Toll Gate]]||26||'''BITUNG'''|| Bitung<br>[[Curug, Tangerang|Curug]]\n|-\n|[[Cikupa|Cikupa Toll Gate]]||31||'''C K P A'''||'''Border of Jakarta\u2013Tangerang Toll Road and Tangerang\u2013Merak Toll Road'''<br>[[Cikupa]]<br>[[Pasar Kemis]]<br> [[Kedaton]]\n|-\n|[[Balaraja|Balaraja Timur Toll Gate]]||37||'''B L J T'''||[[Balaraja|Balaraja Timur]]<br>[[Tigaraksa]]<br>[[Cikupa]]\n|-\n|[[Balaraja|Balaraja Barat Toll Gate]]||39||'''B L J B'''||[[Balaraja|Balaraja Barat]]<br>[[Rangkasbitung]]<br>[[Serpong-Balaraja Toll Road]] (planned)<br>[[Lebak Regency]]\n|-\n|[[Cikande Toll Gate]](planned)||52||'''C K N E'''||[[Cikande]]<br>Industrial\n|-\n|[[Ciujung|Ciujung Toll Gate]]||60||'''C J N G'''||[[Ciujung]]<br> [[Kragilan]]\n|-\n|[[Serang|Serang Timur Toll Gate]]||72||'''S R G T'''||[[Serang|Serang Timur]]<br>[[Pandeglang]]<br> [[Banten Lama]]\n|-\n|[[Serang|Serang Barat Toll Gate]]||78||'''S R G B'''||[[Serang]] <br>[[Kramatwatu]]\n|-\n|[[Cilegon|Cilegon Timur Toll Gate]]||87||'''C L G T'''||[[Cilegon|Cilegon Timur]]<br>[[Bojonegara]]\n|-\n|[[Cilegon|Cilegon Barat Toll Gate]]||95||'''C L G B'''||[[Cilegon|Cilegon Barar]]<br>Anyer Beach<br> [[Carita Beach]]\n|-\n|[[Merak, Banten|Merak Toll Gate]]||98||'''M R A K'''|| [[Merak, Banten|Merak Harbor]]<br>[[Sumatra]]<br>[[Kalimantan]]\n|-\n|[[Bakauheni|Bakauheni Toll Gate]]||120||'''B H N I'''||[[Bakauheni]]<br>Port Of Bakauheni\n|-\n|[[Lampung|Lampung Toll Gate]]||140||'''L M P G'''||[[Lampung]]<br>[[Palembang]]<br> [[Medan-Padang Toll Road]]\n|}\n===Interchange===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! KM !! Location !! Destination\n|-\n|00||[[Tomang]]||[[Jakarta Inner Ring Road]]\n|-\n|08||[[Kembangan, Jakarta|Kembangan]]||[[Jakarta Outer Ring Road]]\n|-\n|38||[[Balaraja]]||[[Serpong\u2013Balaraja Toll Road]] (planned)\n|-\n|140||[[Lampung]]||[[Medan-Padang Toll Road]]\n|}\n\n==Elevated section==\n{{main|Prof. Dr. Sedyatmo Toll Road}}\nIn order to avoid the flood of Ciujung river in the rainy season, the government elevated the road.\n\n==Housing exits==\nThis toll road, not just connecting cities, it also connects housing, here are some:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Toll Gate !! KM !! Housing !! Destination\n|-\n|Karang Tengah Barat||11||[[Green Lake City]]||Green Lake City, Cipondoh, Ciledug\n|-\n|Kunciran||15||[[Alam Sutera]]||Kunciran, [[Alam Sutera]], [[Serpong]]\n|-\n|Karawaci Barat||21||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lippo Village]]||rowspan=\"2\"|Karawaci, Binong, Legok\n|-\n|Karawaci Timur||20||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jakarta-Merak Toll Road}}\n[[Category:Toll roads in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Transport in Banten]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jakarta%E2%80%93Merak_Toll_Road"}
{"title_page": "Italy\u2013Pakistan relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Italy and the Islamic Republic of Pakistan}}\n{{bilateral|Pakistani-Italian|Pakistan|Italy|filetype=svg}}\n\nThe '''Italy\u2013Pakistan relations''' refers to [[Bilateralism|bilateral relations]] between  the [[Italy|Republic of Italy]] and the [[Pakistan|Islamic Republic of Pakistan]]. The nations have cordial relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009/05/20/story_20-5-2009_pg5_11|title=Daily Times|website=Daily Times|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050301004539/http://www.pakistantimes.net/2004/09/29/top.htm|title=Pakistan-Italy oppose UNSC expansion, stress equality|date=1 March 2005|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nItaly is an active investor in Pakistan. Italy provided Pakistan US$100 million under the  Pakistan Italian Debt for Development Swap Agreement to social development projects in health, education and sanitation, in Pakistan<ref>[http://news.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/business/20-pak-italy-sign-$-100-million-agreement-sm-04] {{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref> Italian government has agreed to provide a credit line equivalent to $10 billion for Italian investors willing to invest in Pakistan.<ref>[http://news.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/business/italy-to-provide-$10bn-credit-line-809] {{dead link|date=January 2018}} </ref> Italy has also supported Pakistan bid for [[free-trade area|free trade agreement]] between Pakistan and [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2010/11/11/italy-s-view-by-franco-frattini.html|title=Italy`s view|date=11 November 2010|website=Dawn.com|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are over 150,000 Pakistanis living in Italy, mainly living in the cities of [[Milan]] and [[Brescia]], of whom a vast majority belong to the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] province of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idea.int/resources/analysis/upload/Abbasi_low_2-2.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821142808/http://www.idea.int/resources/analysis/upload/Abbasi_low_2-2.pdf |archivedate=2010-08-21 }}</ref> Pakistan has an embassy in [[Rome]] and a Consulate-General in [[Milan]] for representation, whilst Italy maintains an embassy in [[Islamabad]], a Consulate-General in [[Karachi]] and an honorary consulate in [[Lahore]]. Italy has been a major participant in Pakistan's scientific contribution to the world, and both countries established the International Conference on Astrophysics and Relativity in 2011.\n\nItaly favours a free trade agreement with Pakistan, within the context of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1300682/italy-favours-fta-with-pakistan|title=Italy favours FTA with Pakistan|date=6 December 2016|website=Dawn.com|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Triple Helix Association==\n[[Triple helix model of innovation]], launched by Henry Etzkowitz and [[Loet Leydesdorff]], began in 1996 when a workshop was organized in [[Amsterdam]] to discuss the Triple Helix model. It has been used as a lens through which evolving relationships between university, industry and government can be analyzed. Triple Helix Association was subsequently established in 2009 and headquartered in [[Rome]], [[Italy]] as a non-for-profit, non- governmental association with scientific purpose and a global reach under a main scope is to advance the scientific knowledge and practical achievements related to all aspects of the interaction between academy-industry-government (Triple Helix) for fostering research, innovation, economic competitiveness and growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/about-tha|title=Triple Helix Association (THA)}}</ref>\n\n==THA South Asian Chapter==\nThe Triple Helix Association - South Asian Chapter was headquartered in [[Pakistan]] at [[University of Management and Technology (Lahore)]] in a result of discussions and presentations made at THA conference held in [[Tomsk]], [[Russia]] in September 2014. South Asia Triple Helix Association (SATHA) has been established to spur research, innovation economic growth and regional competitiveness in the region to cope the challenges of growing population and poverty. Among the major challenges of South Asian countries are the weak political, social and economic institutional base which has caused poverty and stagnation. SATHA through its knowledge based activities builds coordinated interactions among the suppliers and users of knowledge. SATHA facilitates the regional universities, industries and governments to articulate strategies for better performance through which more competitiveness, innovation and higher living standards can be achieved. SATHA works with the sub chapters of each country to ensure its regional objectives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/triple-helix-chapter-south-asia-pakistan|title=Triple Helix Chapter South Asia Pakistan}}</ref>\n\n==SATHA Innovation Award 2019==\n\nSATHA Innovation Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/thpost/satha-april-activities-and-results|title=SATHA Innovation Award}}</ref> was established to award those Pakistanis who contribute exceptionally in their respective fields. SATHA Innovation Award is an international award by South Asia Triple Helix Association as part of International Triple Helix Association. On 2 April 2019, South Asia Triple Helix Association (SATHA) launched its Invention to Innovation Summit hosted by [[University of Management and Technology (Lahore)]] to exhibit industry-driven ideas, products and technologies in Pakistan and to award substantial developments and commercially viable technologies. SATHA Innovation Award was granted to Farhan Wilayat Butt on launching the Sindh Water Relief Project<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdgactionawards.org/initiative/1178|title=Sindh Water Relief Project}}</ref>, addressed to construct water-wells and to install hand-pumps in the desert areas of [[Tharparkar]], [[Sindh]].\n\n==Coronavirus crisis==\nIn March 2020, the Italian ministry of foreign affairs reported Pakistan was sending 500,000 chloroquine tablets to help Italian patients suffering from the coronavirus.<ref>https://www.samaa.tv/global/2020/03/pakistan-donating-500000-anti-coronavirus-tablets-to-italy-ministry/</ref>\n\n==Twin cities and towns==\nPakistan and Turkey have many sister cities and twin towns.\n\n* {{flagicon|PAK}} '''[[Multan]]''' and {{flagicon|ITA}} '''[[Rome]]'''\n* {{flagicon|PAK}} '''[[Skardu]]''' and {{flagicon|ITA}} '''[[Cortina d'Ampezzo|Cortina]]'''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pakistanis in Italy]]\n* [[Holy See \u2013 Pakistan relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fisica.unisalento.it/iwra/index.php Italy-Pakistan Workshop on Relativist Astrophysics]\n{{Foreign relations of Pakistan}}\n{{Foreign relations of Italy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Italy-Pakistan relations}}\n[[Category:Italy\u2013Pakistan relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Italy|Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Italy and the Islamic Republic of Pakistan}}\n{{bilateral|Pakistani-Italian|Pakistan|Italy|filetype=svg}}\n\nThe '''Italy\u2013Pakistan relations''' refers to [[Bilateralism|bilateral relations]] between  the [[Italy|Republic of Italy]] and the [[Pakistan|Islamic Republic of Pakistan]]. The nations have cordial relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009/05/20/story_20-5-2009_pg5_11|title=Daily Times|website=Daily Times|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050301004539/http://www.pakistantimes.net/2004/09/29/top.htm|title=Pakistan-Italy oppose UNSC expansion, stress equality|date=1 March 2005|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nItaly is an active investor in Pakistan. Italy provided Pakistan US$100 million under the  Pakistan Italian Debt for Development Swap Agreement to social development projects in health, education and sanitation, in Pakistan<ref>[http://news.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/business/20-pak-italy-sign-$-100-million-agreement-sm-04] {{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref> Italian government has agreed to provide a credit line equivalent to $10 billion for Italian investors willing to invest in Pakistan.<ref>[http://news.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/business/italy-to-provide-$10bn-credit-line-809] {{dead link|date=January 2018}} </ref> Italy has also supported Pakistan bid for [[free-trade area|free trade agreement]] between Pakistan and [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/2010/11/11/italy-s-view-by-franco-frattini.html|title=Italy`s view|date=11 November 2010|website=Dawn.com|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are over 150,000 Pakistanis living in Italy, mainly living in the cities of [[Milan]] and [[Brescia]], of whom a vast majority belong to the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] province of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idea.int/resources/analysis/upload/Abbasi_low_2-2.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821142808/http://www.idea.int/resources/analysis/upload/Abbasi_low_2-2.pdf |archivedate=2010-08-21 }}</ref> Pakistan has an embassy in [[Rome]] and a Consulate-General in [[Milan]] for representation, whilst Italy maintains an embassy in [[Islamabad]], a Consulate-General in [[Karachi]] and an honorary consulate in [[Lahore]]. Italy has been a major participant in Pakistan's scientific contribution to the world, and both countries established the International Conference on Astrophysics and Relativity in 2011.\n\nItaly favours a free trade agreement with Pakistan, within the context of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1300682/italy-favours-fta-with-pakistan|title=Italy favours FTA with Pakistan|date=6 December 2016|website=Dawn.com|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Triple Helix Association==\n[[Triple helix model of innovation]], launched by Henry Etzkowitz and [[Loet Leydesdorff]], began in 1996 when a workshop was organized in [[Amsterdam]] to discuss the Triple Helix model. It has been used as a lens through which evolving relationships between university, industry and government can be analyzed. Triple Helix Association was subsequently established in 2009 and headquartered in [[Rome]], [[Italy]] as a non-for-profit, non- governmental association with scientific purpose and a global reach under a main scope is to advance the scientific knowledge and practical achievements related to all aspects of the interaction between academy-industry-government (Triple Helix) for fostering research, innovation, economic competitiveness and growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/about-tha|title=Triple Helix Association (THA)}}</ref>\n\n==THA South Asian Chapter==\nThe Triple Helix Association - South Asian Chapter was headquartered in [[Pakistan]] at [[University of Management and Technology (Lahore)]] in a result of discussions and presentations made at THA conference held in [[Tomsk]], [[Russia]] in September 2014. South Asia Triple Helix Association (SATHA) has been established to spur research, innovation economic growth and regional competitiveness in the region to cope the challenges of growing population and poverty. Among the major challenges of South Asian countries are the weak political, social and economic institutional base which has caused poverty and stagnation. SATHA through its knowledge based activities builds coordinated interactions among the suppliers and users of knowledge. SATHA facilitates the regional universities, industries and governments to articulate strategies for better performance through which more competitiveness, innovation and higher living standards can be achieved. SATHA works with the sub chapters of each country to ensure its regional objectives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/triple-helix-chapter-south-asia-pakistan|title=Triple Helix Chapter South Asia Pakistan}}</ref>\n\n==SATHA Innovation Award 2019==\n\nSATHA Innovation Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.triplehelixassociation.org/thpost/satha-april-activities-and-results|title=SATHA Innovation Award}}</ref> was established to award those Pakistanis who contribute exceptionally in their respective fields. SATHA Innovation Award is an international award by South Asia Triple Helix Association as part of International Triple Helix Association. On 2 April 2019, South Asia Triple Helix Association (SATHA) launched its Invention to Innovation Summit hosted by [[University of Management and Technology (Lahore)]] to exhibit industry-driven ideas, products and technologies in Pakistan and to award substantial developments and commercially viable technologies. SATHA Innovation Award was granted to Farhan Wilayat Butt on launching the Sindh Water Relief Project<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sdgactionawards.org/initiative/1178|title=Sindh Water Relief Project}}</ref>, addressed to construct water-wells and to install hand-pumps in the desert areas of [[Tharparkar]], [[Sindh]].\n\n==Coronavirus crisis==\nIn March 2020, the Italian ministry of foreign affairs reported Pakistan was sending 500,000 chloroquine tablets to help Italian patients suffering from the coronavirus.<ref>https://www.samaa.tv/global/2020/03/pakistan-donating-500000-anti-coronavirus-tablets-to-italy-ministry/</ref>\n\n==Twin cities and towns==\nPakistan and Turkey have many sister cities and twin towns.\n\n* {{fla